  "context_summary": "26-year-old man presenting with several months of progressive, dull, generalized mid-to-lower back pain rated 4-5/10. The pain came on insidiously without trauma, has been getting worse, and is partially relieved by ibuprofen. He also reports intermittent pain in his right knee and hands over the same timeline, increased fatigue and malaise, and a recent episode of gastroenteritis a few months ago treated with antibiotics. His mother has psoriasis. The doctor has just learned the pain is worse in the morning.",
  "good_next_question": "Approximately how much time would you say after you wake up, the stiffness and pain goes away?",
  "rationale": "This question quantifies morning stiffness duration, the single most useful bedside discriminator between inflammatory and mechanical back pain. Morning-worse back pain in a young man is suggestive but not specific — mechanical back pain can also feel worse on waking due to overnight stillness, and the duration of stiffness is what separates the two patterns. Mechanical stiffness typically resolves within a few minutes to half an hour of getting up; inflammatory stiffness (ankylosing spondylitis, psoriatic arthritis, reactive arthritis, IBD-associated arthritis) characteristically lasts greater than 30-60 minutes and improves with activity rather than rest. The doctor is testing a specific quantitative feature from the ASAS inflammatory back pain criteria rather than asking another generic pain-character question. A few-minutes answer keeps mechanical causes on top; a long-duration answer combined with his age under 40, insidious onset, peripheral joint involvement, family history of psoriasis, and recent GI infection (reactive arthritis trigger) reorders the workup decisively toward HLA-B27, SI joint imaging, inflammatory markers, and rheumatology referral.",
  "tags": [
    "back_pain",
    "young_male",
    "musculoskeletal",
    "autoimmune",
    "pattern_recognition",
    "spondyloarthropathy"
  ],
